{"about 1133–":"oko 1133.–preminuo","–Female":"preminula","1159–Female":"1159–preminula","1133–Male":"1133–preminuo","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"oko 1159.","about 1133":"oko 1133.","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"cs":{"about 1133–":"okolo 1133–Zesnulý","–Female":"Zesnulá","1159–Female":"1159–Zesnulá","1133–Male":"1133–Zesnulý","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"okolo 1159","about 1133":"okolo 1133","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1133–":"omkring 1133–Afdød","–Female":"Afdød","1159–Female":"1159–Afdød","1133–Male":"1133–Afdød","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"omkring 1159","about 1133":"omkring 1133","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1133–":"circa 1133–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1159–Female":"1159–Overleden","1133–Male":"1133–Overleden","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"circa 1159","about 1133":"circa 1133","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1133–":"about 1133–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1159–Female":"1159–Deceased","1133–Male":"1133–Deceased","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"about 1159","about 1133":"about 1133","Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Auke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>duk(ke)</i>, <i>duck</i>, <i>doke</i>, <i>dook</i> ‘duck’ (Old English <i>dūce</i>), either from a perceived resemblance (perhaps a waddling gait) or from association with wild fowling. Compare   Duck  ,   Drake  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Duk</i> or <i>Duke</i>. In northern England this is usually a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>. It may alternatively be a survival of one or more Old English personal names, though it is uncertain whether they were still current in the period of surname formation. Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i> is attested in placenames like Duxford (Cambridgeshire) and Duckington (Cheshire), and was perhaps interchangeable with <i>Docc</i>, attested in Doxey (Staffordshire) and Doxford (Northumberland). <i>Duke</i> could also represent Old English <i>Deowuc</i> (as in Deuxhill, Shropshire). A surname from <i>Marmaduke</i> is on record until at least 1881 and derives from the personal name <i>Marmaduke</i>, apparently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of Old Irish <i>Maolmaedóc</i> ‘devotee of <i>Maedóc</i>’; see   Duckett  .","Americanized form of Polish <b>Duk</b>: nickname from <i>dukać</i> ‘to stammer or falter’."],"variants":[{"name":"Dock","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Duke  .","Norwegian: habitational name from a farm named Dokk, from Old Norse <i>dǫkk</i> ‘hollow, depression’.","North German (Lower Saxony): possibly a metonymic occupational name for someone who worked in the cloth trade, from Middle Low German <i>dōk</i> ‘fabric’."]},{"name":"Doke","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  ."]},{"name":"Duch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Nga, Phal, Phan, Sophan, Tha, Thang, Yen.  German Kurt, Klaus.","Polish, Sorbian, and Ukrainian: nickname from <i>duch</i> ‘spirit, breath’.","Czech: from a short form of the Old Czech personal name <i>Duchoslav</i>, composed of the elements <i>duch</i> ‘spirit’ + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Duckett","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): from the Middle English personal name <i>Duket</i>. This may sometimes have been an early Middle English pet form of an Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."]},{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Dukes","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Gregory","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Gregory Auke was born about 1133, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with unknown."},"et":{"about 1133–":"umbes 1133–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1159–Female":"1159–Surnud","1133–Male":"1133–Surnud","1159":"1159","1133":"1133","about 1159":"umbes 1159","about 1133":"umbes 1133","L